SCENE V.

Pontus'roa enters, affecting sympathy with Hecuba in her missor· tunes (vv, 953-967). Hecuba aske him to excuse her not venturing to look him in the face in her slavish condition; makes enquiries about Polydorus, to display the ruthlessness of Polymestor's character, and at last tempts him into her tent by telling him that, besides treasurcs hidden underground in Troy, she has some with her, which she has hitherto saved from the eyes of the Greeks (vv. 968-1022).
